Anil and Rita Philip wrote:

&gt; I shall try to explain more clearly:
&gt;
&gt; if(some condition is true) {
&gt;         do some work;
&gt;         return result1;
&gt; }
&gt; else {
&gt;         do some other work;
&gt;         return result2;
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; Here are two execution paths within a procedure. Both
&gt; result1 and result2 might be identical in value some
&gt; of the time, for a many to one function. Using Junit,
&gt; how can one know that both paths have been exercised
&gt; or tested?
&gt;

My first move here would be to ensure that the code looks like this:


    if (some condition is true) {
        return doSomeWork();
    }
    else {
        return doSomeOtherWork();
    }


(Note that the work is being performed in other methods, rather than in
inlined code.)

Then I&#39;d write tests for both doSomeWork() and doSomeOtherWork() to verify
that they return the expected results in context.

Then I&#39;d probably write a test for the code above to verify that it returns
the expected result when the condition is both true and false.

